# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: john-page-virginia-politician
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/1797-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on December 7, 1797.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/1797-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia James Wood defeated the U.S. representative from Virginia's 12th congressional district John Page.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/1797-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Wood had earned the displeasure of his fellow Democratic-Republicans for his inaction in the face of the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/1797-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Some Democratic-Republicans preferred to support the former U.S. minister to France James Monroe, an outspoken critic of the legislation.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/1797-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Monroe, however, declined to challenge Wood, in deference to the custom that incumbent governors eligible for re-election be allowed to run unopposed.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/1797-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election was conducted by the Virginia General Assembly in joint session.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/1797-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Wood was elected with a majority on the first ballot.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] Robertson was born in Martinsburg, West Virginia, the son of Franklin Pierce Robertson and Josephine Ragland (née Willis), just two weeks before fellow Virginia Senator Harry F.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] He graduated from the University of Richmond in 1907.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] Robertson established a private law practice following graduation, and soon embarked on a political career.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] He was elected to the Virginia State Senate as a Democrat in 1915 to represent Bedford and Rockbridge counties and Buena Vista, Virginia, in Senate district 22, replacing W.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] Robertson served from 1916 to 1922, when he resigned and was replaced by Samuel S.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] Lambeth Jr. in the February 1923 special session.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] The constituency was renumbered as the 23rd district in advance of the General Assembly's 1924 session.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] During World War I, Robertson enlisted and served in the United States Army, but was assigned stateside so he could continue that part-time elective office.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] Robertson served as Commonwealth Attorney for Rockbridge County, Virginia (an elective office per the Virginia constitution, which prohibited such officials from also serving as legislators or judges during their terms) from 1922 to 1928.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] In 1932, Robertson was elected from Virginia's 7th congressional district to the U.S.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] House of Representatives, and was reelected six times.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] In 1946, he won a special election for the right to complete the final two years of Senator Carter Glass's term and took office on the day after the election.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] He won the seat in his own right in 1948 and was reelected two more times without serious opposition.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] Among his legislation is the Pittman–Robertson Federal Aid in Wildlife Restoration Act which creates the formula for federal sharing of ammunition tax revenues with states to establish wildlife areas.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] The program is still in effect and remains a primary financing source for wildlife areas.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] Robertson was a typical member of the Byrd Organization, though his opinions differed at times and eventually became independent from the machine.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] Senate Committee on Banking, Housing, and Urban Affairs from 1959 to 1966.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] In 1956, Robertson was one of the 19 senators who signed the Southern Manifesto against the U.S.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] Board of Education of Topeka* (1954), which mandated schools' desegregation.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] Johnson sent his wife, Lady Bird Johnson, on a train trip through the South to encourage support for the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and the Voting Rights Act of 1965, Robertson was one of four Southern Senators who refused to meet with her on the whistle-stop trip.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] In retaliation, President Johnson personally recruited Virginia State Senator William B.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] Spong Jr., a considerably more liberal Democrat, to run against Robertson in the 1966 Democratic primary.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] Even some Byrd Democrats had moved away from resistance to integration as espoused by Robertson and the Organization's patriarch, Harry F.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] Meanwhile, the Twenty-Fourth Amendment and Voting Rights Act had combined to add black and lower-income voters.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] Spong defeated Robertson in the primary in one of the biggest upsets in Virginia political history.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] The Byrd Organization's long dominance of Virginia state politics had begun to end.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] In 1971, Robertson died in Lexington, Virginia and is buried in Stonewall Jackson Memorial Cemetery, later renamed Oak Grove Cemetery.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/a-willis-robertson] His papers are held at the Swem Library at the College of William and Mary.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was born in New Jersey and moved frequently during her childhood before her family settled in Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She earned degrees from the University of Virginia and Purdue University.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] From 2006 to 2014, she was an officer in the Central Intelligence Agency.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] House of Representatives in 2018, unseating incumbent Republican Dave Brat.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was reelected in 2020 and 2022 before leaving Congress to run for governor.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was elected governor of Virginia in 2025, defeating the Republican nominee, Lieutenant Governor Winsome Earle-Sears.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She is Virginia's first female governor.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] As governor, Spanberger signed a controversial "assault weapons" ban, increased the state's minimum wage, vetoed recreational cannabis retail market and collective bargaining legislation, and supported the 2026 Virginia redistricting referendum.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was born Abigail Anne Davis in Red Bank, New Jersey, on August 7, 1979, her father, Martin Davis, a police officer, and her mother, Eileen Davis, a nurse.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She knew from a young age that she wanted to be a spy, writing her diary in code.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her family moved often when she was young, living in Maine, the New York City area, and Philadelphia, before settling in Short Pump, Virginia, when she was 13.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her father had moved from policing to federal law enforcement for the United States Postal Inspection Service.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She graduated from John Randolph Tucker High School and was later a page for U.S. senator Chuck Robb.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger earned a Bachelor of Arts from the University of Virginia in 2001 and a Master of Business Administration from a joint program between the GISMA Business School in Germany and Purdue University's Krannert School of Management.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She initially enrolled at the College of William and Mary before transferring to the University of Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] According to her sister Meredith Schatz, by the time she had completed her undergraduate degree at the University of Virginia, Spanberger was conversationally fluent in Spanish and "five or six more" languages.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] In the early 2000s, Spanberger taught English literature as a substitute teacher at the Islamic Saudi Academy in Northern Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She received a conditional job offer from the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) in December 2002.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] While waiting for a background check to be completed, Spanberger worked as a postal inspector, as her father did, focusing on money laundering and narcotics cases.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] In July 2006, after Spanberger's background check had been completed, she joined the CIA as a case officer, working to find, recruit, and build relationships with foreign nationals who could have had information of value to the U.S. government.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She has publicly said that she gathered intelligence about nuclear proliferation and terrorism.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her first assignment was to Brussels, according to *The Washington Post*.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] During her career, she held, at some point, five different passports, and met people undercover.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] In 2014, Spanberger left the CIA and entered the private sector.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was hired by Royall & Company (now a part of EAB) to do consulting work for colleges and universities.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] After the 2016 presidential election, she began working with Emerge America to encourage women to run for state and congressional offices.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] In 2017, Virginia governor Terry McAuliffe appointed her to the Virginia Fair Housing Board.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] In July 2017, Spanberger announced her candidacy for the United States House of Representatives in Virginia's 7th congressional district in the 2018 election against incumbent Republican Dave Brat, a former Tea Party movement member.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She had begun to consider challenging Brat after attending a town hall meeting he hosted in Nottoway County in February 2017 and made the final decision to run in May after the House voted to repeal the Affordable Care Act, texting her husband, "I'm gonna run and I'm gonna f---ing win".
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 12, 2018, Spanberger defeated Dan Ward in the Democratic primary election with 73% of the vote, receiving more votes than any other candidate in the Virginia primaries that day.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] In June, after winning the primary, while waiting for a train at the Richmond Staples Mill Road Amtrak station, Spanberger met William C.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Mims, a justice on the Supreme Court of Virginia, who told her he was "impressed with her message".
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] In August, the Congressional Leadership Fund, a super PAC closely aligned with Republican House Speaker Paul Ryan, conducted a smear campaign against Spanberger.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The campaign, which attempted to tie her to terrorism, was based on an SF-86 application she completed to obtain security clearance, which was released in breach of privacy rules.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] In a visit to the district, former Trump adviser Steve Bannon called the race "an absolute bellwether of the entire country" and said that losing it would mean Republican loss of control of the House.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger won the November 6 general election by about 6,800 votes.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Brat won eight of the district's ten counties, but Spanberger dominated the two largest counties, Henrico and Chesterfield, by a combined margin of over 30,000 votes.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] After winning the election, Virginia Supreme Court Justice Mims wrote her a letter extolling the virtues of public service, leadership, and civility, alongside a copy of former Czech President Václav Havel's essay "Politics, Morality, and Civility".
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger has said the letter and its impact on her leadership were crucial to her development as a politician.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was the first Democrat to win this seat since 1970, when four-term Democrat John Marsh retired and was succeeded by Republican J.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] But until 1993, the 7th stretched from the outer Washington suburbs through the Shenandoah Valley and Charlottesville to the outer Richmond suburbs; the present 7th is geographically and demographically the successor to what was the 3rd district before 1993.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] That district had been in Republican hands since 1981; former House majority leader Eric Cantor represented it from 2001 until Brat ousted him in the 2014 Republican primary.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger and her colleagues Elissa Slotkin and Mikie Sherrill were described as the "mod squad", a moderate alternative to the progressive "squad".
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger and Sherrill shared a Capitol Hill apartment for four years while they served in Congress together.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger faced a close reelection contest against Virginia delegate Nick Freitas, who represented much of the congressional district's northern portion.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She won with 51% of the vote to Freitas's 49%.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Freitas carried eight of the district's ten counties, as Brat had done two years earlier, but Spanberger prevailed by winning the district's shares of Henrico and Chesterfield counties by a combined 43,400 votes, five times her overall margin of 8,400 votes.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was also boosted by Joe Biden narrowly carrying the district; Biden was the first Democrat to win what is now the 7th Congressional District since 1948.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On November 5, days after winning reelection by a margin of 1.8%, Spanberger criticized the Democratic Party's strategy for the 2020 elections in a phone call with other Democratic caucus members that was subsequently leaked.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Calling the elections "a failure" from a congressional standpoint, she singled out Republican attack ads decrying "socialism" and the movement to "defund the police" as prime reasons the Democratic Party lost seats in swing districts.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger argued that Democrats should watch Republican ads before deciding how to talk about issues and never "use the word 'socialist' or 'socialism' ever again".
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] After the 2020 elections, Spanberger criticized Democratic messaging, arguing that progressive slogans such as "defund the police" and "socialism" had hurt candidates in swing districts.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] CNN political editor Chris Cillizza called her comments "hard truth" for the Democratic Party, adding that for Democrats to succeed in the 2022 and 2024 elections, they should "listen to the likes of Spanberger" rather than push for "the boldest possible progressive legislation".
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] For her first two terms, Spanberger represented a district that stretched from the Richmond suburbs to the fringes of the Shenandoah Valley.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] After the 2020 United States redistricting cycle, Spanberger's district was radically redrawn, and no longer included her home in Henrico County.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She considered not running for reelection in the new district before deciding to do so.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was seen as one of the most vulnerable incumbents of the 2022 election cycle, with pre-election polls projecting a close race with Republican Prince William County supervisor Yesli Vega, a law enforcement officer endorsed by Governor Glenn Youngkin and former president Donald Trump.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger defeated Vega, 52% to 48%, the largest margin at the time in any election Spanberger had run in.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] According to *FiveThirtyEight*'s congressional vote tracker, Spanberger voted with President Trump 8.7% of the time.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] In the 2016 presidential election, Trump won 50% of the vote to Hillary Clinton's 44% in Spanberger's future congressional district.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On September 23, 2019, Spanberger joined six other freshman House Democrats with national security backgrounds in calling for an impeachment inquiry into Trump.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger later announced that she would vote in favor of impeachment, saying, "The President's actions violate his oath of office, endanger our national security, and betray the public trust".
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 1, 2020, Spanberger tweeted criticism of Trump's reaction to the George Floyd protests, a series of protests against police brutality that began in Minneapolis on May 26.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 2, *The Washington Post* and *The New York Times* quoted Spanberger and several other high-profile former CIA analysts' interpretations of Trump's reaction to the protests as reminiscent of the reaction of totalitarian dictators on the brink of losing control of their dictatorships.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] "As a former CIA officer, I know this playbook, and I know the president's actions are betraying the very foundation of the rule of law he purports to support, the U.S.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger criticized Trump after police used tear gas and rubber bullets on peaceful protestors and a priest during the George Floyd protests to clear a path so that he could have a photo op in front of St.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger opposed Democrats' attempts to amend the Insurrection Act of 1807, saying that amending the rarely used law would not accomplish what Democrats intended.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] According to *PolitiFact*, Spanberger publicly disagreed with some of Biden's immigration policies that have not been subject to congressional votes, but she voted for all 73 bills and resolutions in the House of Representatives that Biden voiced support for.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] In December 2023, she was one of six House Democrats to send Biden a letter criticizing Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's Gaza military strategy.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] In 2020, during a meeting with then-Governor of Virginia Ralph Northam, Northam suggested she should run for governor someday.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger took his advice, and in November 2023 announced that she would not seek reelection to Congress and would instead run for governor of Virginia in the 2025 election.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She secured the uncontested nomination in April 2025.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] In May 2025, while campaigning, Spanberger said she would not sign a bill to fully repeal Virginia's right-to-work law if elected governor.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger is one of the few Virginia gubernatorial candidates to refuse money from Dominion Energy, instead getting donations from the anti-Dominion watchdog Clean Virginia alongside her running mates, who defeated Dominion-backed candidates.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her priorities on immigration include scrapping Youngkin's immigration order allowing local police to help carry out Trump's ICE raids and deportation policy.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She supports rejoining the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative, which Youngkin, a Republican, left after Northam had joined it.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was elected in a landslide, securing 58% of the vote.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Republican nominee, incumbent lieutenant governor Winsome Earle-Sears, received 42%.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] It was the largest margin of victory for a Democratic gubernatorial candidate in Virginia since Albertis Harrison received just under 64% of the vote in 1961.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The official vote margin was over 527,000.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] While Democrats won the three statewide races in Virginia in 2025, Spanberger's 15-point margin of victory was the largest.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger outperformed Kamala Harris in the 2024 presidential election in the state by nearly 10 percentage points, while winning 99% of Harris's voters.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On November 5, Spanberger announced her transition team, which included Chris Lu, Daun Hester, and Yohannes Abraham.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Honorary co-chairs of the team included many Democratic Party of Virginia leaders, such as Louise Lucas, Don Scott, Jennifer Wexton, and Rick Boucher.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger's transition informally began on November 6 with a lunch with Governor Youngkin.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On November 12, Spanberger asked the University of Virginia's board of visitors to pause its search for a new president until her transition was complete, drawing criticism from both Youngkin and conservative alumni of the university for supposed politicization of the board process.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger said Youngkin had done the same during his tenure, and promised structural reform to prevent it.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger made her first cabinet appointment on December 2, announcing Marvin Figueroa as Secretary of Health and Human Resources, and continued to make appointments throughout the month.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was sworn in as governor on January 17, 2026.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was sworn in by former Supreme Court of Virginia Justice William C.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Mims, with her husband Adam holding the Bible and her daughters by her side.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On January 17, 2026, her first day in office, Spanberger signed ten executive orders focusing primarily on affordability, healthcare, housing, education, and preparedness for potential federal policy changes under the Trump administration.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] One of Spanberger's first challenges as governor was managing the January 2026 North American winter storm, responsible for the deaths of four people and hundreds of traffic accidents.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On January 30, Spanberger described the Virginia Leaders in Export Trade (VALET) program, promoting free trade in opposition to Trump's tariffs.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Virginia Port Authority is a major hub of international trade.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On January 19, 2026, Spanberger delivered her first address to a joint session of the Virginia General Assembly, emphasizing affordability, bipartisanship, and pragmatic solutions.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She committed to reentering the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative (RGGI), maintaining Virginia's right-to-work law, collaborating with the federal government where possible, and pushing back against policies harming Virginia jobs or families.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She outlined legislative priorities including lowering healthcare and energy costs, protecting renters, expanding housing production, supporting agriculture amid tariffs, implementing pro-worker measures such as paid family leave and a higher minimum wage, and bipartisan gun safety bills.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Republicans welcomed the calls for unity and right-to-work commitment but proposed alternative tax relief measures and cautioned against increased spending.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger, who campaigned in support of these amendments, said she would campaign for their passage.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] HB736 limits prior authorizations for prescription medication that can lead to costly delays in care.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 30, 2026, the Faith in Housing Act was signed into law.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] It eliminates the rezoning step for faith-based organizations and other tax-exempt nonprofits to develop affordable housing on their properties, allowing religious organizations to give their communities affordable housing with fewer regulatory restrictions.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] SB377 allows utilities to cooperate with high-load energy users to build new substations that exclusively serve them, at the expense of the energy user, to shield other ratepayers from increased costs incurred by their intensive consumption.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger returned the bill to the legislature with amendments on April 13, 2026.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Another amendment removed an exemption for high-load projects approved before July 1, 2026.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The General Assembly accepted these amendments while rejecting a number of other amendments to the bill.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Shortly after taking office in January 2026, Spanberger reiterated a pledge and long-term policy goal of the state Democratic Party to rejoin the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative in her first address to the General Assembly.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 22, to commemorate Earth Day, Spanberger signed an executive order committing Virginia to the United States Climate Alliance, a bipartisan coalition of governors committed to sustaining America's fight against climate change with state-led action.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] In May, she signed a slate of legislation aimed at preserving the state's natural resources and treating drinking water for PFAS compounds.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 8, she signed into law HB507, which prohibits the Virginia Department of Environmental Quality from issuing air permits to data centers with backup diesel gen-sets that do not satisfy the Environmental Protection Agency's tier 4 emission standards.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] During her campaign, Spanberger committed to expanding the state's solar and wind energy capacity.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On March 25, Spanberger created the cabinet-level position of Chief Energy Officer via executive order, appointing Southern Environmental Law Center attorney Josephus Allmond to the position.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The office is tasked with cooperating with the Virginia Secretary of Commerce and Trade, the Virginia Department of Energy, PJM Interconnection, and energy utility providers to address rising energy costs, expand clean energy generation, and develop a statewide energy strategy.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She later signed HB1444, formally codifying the Clean Energy Innovation Bank that had been trialed by the Virginia Department of Energy in 2024, which financed clean energy projects, greenhouse gas emissions reduction projects, and other similar projects.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The recission order does not force local departments to exit existing agreements with ICE.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Nevertheless, the order has been criticized by Republicans and ICE officials, who have called it a "sanctuary state" policy that has led to an increase in immigrant crime.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] At the same time, she vetoed a law that would have prevented ICE from conducting civil arrests at courthouses, schools, and healthcare facilities.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Virginia House of Delegates voted to approve an amendment enshrining abortion access for all Virginia citizens shortly before Spanberger took office.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Senate followed suit shortly thereafter.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger signed the bill and sent it to the voters for final approval on February 6, 2026.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 8, Spanberger signed the Right to Contraception Act, enshrining Virginians' right to obtain and use contraceptive drugs or devices and healthcare providers' right to provide them.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 6, 2026, Spanberger signed into law HB1, which would increase the state's hourly minimum wage from $12.77 to $13.75 by January 1, 2027, and $15 by 2028; thereafter the minimum wage will be indexed to increases in the consumer price index and hiked incrementally every year.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Two days later, she signed HB20, which rescinded a statutory exemption from the state minimum wage law for farm laborers and employees, which would go into effect on January 1, 2027.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On May 11, 2026, Spanberger signed a bill establishing a Paid Family and Medical Leave Insurance program administered by the Virginia Employment Commission, set to go into effect in 2028.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The program will be funded by a trust fund financed by remittances from employers deducted from employee payrolls and, for employers of more than ten workers, employer contributions.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The law extends benefits to over 1.2 million uncovered workers.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 22, she signed the Equal Pay Act, which prohibits employers from querying prospective workers about their pay history and using that data in considering whether to hire them or in determining their salary unless they voluntarily provide their pay history.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She also signed a bill that expands legal protections against wage theft.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 26, 2026, Spanberger signed legislation hiking benefits for unemployment claims filed after July 5 of that year by 11.2%, from $430 to $478 per week.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On May 14, 2026, Spanberger vetoed SB378 and HB1263, collective bargaining legislation backed by the Virginia Service Employees International Union (SEIU) and various labor groups.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] HB542 was the state legislature's most recent effort to expand the commercial sale of recreational cannabis.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] It would have established a framework for the creation of a cannabis retail market administered and regulated by the Virginia Cannabis Control Authority and partially liberalized certain restrictions on sales quantities.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The General Assembly rejected these recommendations.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] As a result, Spanberger vetoed the bill on May 19, 2026, despite supporting the creation of a retail cannabis market as long as it had strong labeling and regulation.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She cited the bill's "rushed timeframe", which she said gave the state too little time to design comprehensive strategies for regulating the market or to learn from the successes and errors of other states that liberalized cannabis retailing.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Negotiations continued in the following weeks, and they reached a compromise on June 16.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Semi-automatic shotguns for hunting are not considered assault weapons, and semi-automatic firearms owned before July 1 may be retained.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The law was subject to litigation immediately after being enacted.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] She signed other restrictions relating to the possession of firearms in hospitals, the presence of polling places, and laws relating to gun owners' responsibility to keep their firearms secure.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Bypassing the commission would require another amendment to the Constitution of Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The General Assembly can pass amendments through a majority vote by the House of Delegates and the Senate in two consecutive legislative sessions, which would send the amendment to be approved by the voters as a ballot measure.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] A corresponding resolution was adopted by the Assembly in October that allows the Virginia General Assembly to consider constitutional amendments related to redistricting during a special session, which was agreed to by the House on the 29th and by the Senate on the 31st.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Both floors reapproved the amendment after the beginning of 164th General Assembly, and Spanberger signed the legislation that sent it to the voters.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The amendment was ultimately approved, 51.69% to 48.31%.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] It was struck down by the Supreme Court of Virginia on May 8, a ruling appealed by state Democrats.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Supreme Court rejected the appeal on May 15.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] On February 24, 2026, Spanberger delivered the Democratic response to Trump's 2026 State of the Union Address from the chamber of the House of Burgesses in the reconstructed Capitol in Williamsburg, Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Hodges* is overturned, and the Voting Rights Restoration Amendment, which restores voting rights to formerly incarcerated people who completed felony sentences.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] The 2026 legislative session concluded on March 14 with sine die adjournment without a final biennial budget agreement, due to a dispute over data center tax exemptions.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] In April 2026, Spanberger signed a bill that eliminates tax breaks for organizations related to the Confederate States of America, and a package of legislation relating to maternal healthcare and telemedicine.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Most bills would take effect on July 1, 2026.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Very early in Spanberger's governorship, opinion polls showed that her job approval rating was fairly stable and similar to the average of previous Virginia governors.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] A poll by the Institute for Policy and Opinion Research at Roanoke College in early February showed that 53% of Virginians gave her high marks for her job performance, while 38% disapproved.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] By April, her approval rating had dropped significantly, with a *Washington Post*–Schar School poll finding that 47% of voters approved of Spanberger and 46% disapproved.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] This marked the worst net approval rating for a governor in the early months of their term in *Washington Post* polls since the early 1990s.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] Similarly, a State Navigate poll conducted on April 10–13 showed her net approval rating to be breaking even.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] But after the 2026 Virginia redistricting amendment, a *Public Sentiment Institute* poll found that 52% of voters approved of Spanberger and 41% disapproved, as in earlier polls.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p01] In June 2026, *Vox* described Spanberger as polarizing, attempting to placate both businesses and Democrats, while being viewed negatively by Republicans.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger positions herself as a moderate Democrat and has called herself a "passionate pragmatist".
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] In the 2019 speaker of the United States House of Representatives election on the opening day of the 116th United States Congress, Spanberger voted for Representative Cheri Bustos, an Illinois Democrat, joining 11 other Democrats who did not back Nancy Pelosi.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, overturning the right to abortion established by *Roe v.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Wade*, saying that "it undermines the right to privacy and a woman's right to choose".
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] She opposes legislation to restrict abortion, saying that the government should not "mandate a pregnancy".
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] During her gubernatorial campaign, Spanberger said she would support a constitutional amendment to restore "the *Roe* standard" and that she supported Virginia's existing laws requiring minors seeking abortions to receive parental consent, and certain limitations on third-trimester abortions.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] In February 2023, Spanberger was one of 12 House Democrats who voted in favor of H.J.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] 7, a Republican-sponsored resolution to terminate the national emergency concerning COVID-19 declared in March 2020.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] During her 2025 campaign for governor of Virginia, a January 6, 2021, photograph of Spanberger wearing an emergency escape hood inside the Capitol was circulated online by critics, who misrepresented it as COVID-19 protective gear and mocked her.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] In 2023, Spanberger voted against overturning the District of Columbia's revision of its criminal code, which reduced the maximum penalties for burglary, carjacking, and robbery.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger opposes defunding the police, and has supported bills that would increase the ability of local police departments to hire and train more officers.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Although she was not a member of Congress when it passed, Spanberger criticized the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act supported by President Donald Trump, arguing that its permanent tax cuts for corporations would increase the national debt.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger called for the passage of the USMCA trade deal negotiated by the Trump administration, Mexico, and Canada.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger opposed Trump's tariffs during her 2025 gubernatorial campaign.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] She has promoted free trade during her tenure as governor.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] In May 2020, Spanberger voted against the HEROES Act, a proposed $3 trillion stimulus package in response to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] She said the bill went "far beyond" pandemic relief and had no chance of passing the Republican-controlled Senate.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] In November 2020, Spanberger led a bipartisan effort to secure the 340B Drug Pricing Program against changes that would lead to significant increases in prescription medication costs.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger supports banning members of Congress from trading stocks.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] She has introduced legislation that would require lawmakers, as well as their spouses and dependent children, to place assets in a blind trust while in office.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] In September 2025, Spanberger wrote an opinion article in *The Washington Post* opposing DOGE for conducting mass layoffs of federal workers in 2025 which particularly affect Virginia, as many federal workers live there.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger focused her 2025 gubernatorial campaign on affordability and jobs.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Through her "Strengthening Virginia Schools Plan", Spanberger announced she would make higher education more affordable and accessible and make it easier for high school students to take college-level courses.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] She supports allowing teachers to deliver instruction and manage curriculum without interference from political bodies or agendas.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger has emphasized strengthening public schools by hiring and fairly compensating teachers, rather than supporting private schools and school choice.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger has called climate change "one of the greatest and most imminent threats to our economy, our national security, and our way of life" and said she will "stand up to attacks against science".
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] During a 2019 Committee on Foreign Affairs meeting, she asked the Trump administration to reverse its isolationist policies, saying, "it's in our national interest to reinforce our stature as a global leader on international environmental and energy issues".
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger called the Green New Deal proposed by Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez a "bold compilation of ideas meant to address global climate change" but criticized it for allegedly including unrelated policy proposals and not identifying specific resolutions to the problems that it identifies.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] "Overall I am not a supporter of the Green New Deal", she said.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] In February 2023, during the Russo–Ukrainian War, Spanberger signed a letter advocating that President Biden give Ukraine F-16 fighter jets.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] In June 2025, Spanberger supported the U.S. strikes on Iranian nuclear sites.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger has called for a new version of the Federal Assault Weapons Ban that expired in 2004.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] She favors requiring background checks on private gun sales and supported a ban on bump stocks.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Before she served in Congress, Spanberger volunteered with Moms Demand Action, a gun-control advocacy group.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger supports the Affordable Care Act (Obamacare).
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] She supports a public option for healthcare via the proposed Medicare-X Choice Act.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] In November 2020, she called reducing the cost of prescription drugs "the top priority of families in my district".
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] In January 2020, Spanberger sponsored the Public Disclosure of Drug Discounts Act, which passed the House unanimously.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] The bill requires pharmacy benefit managers (PBMs), who manage prescription drug benefits for health insurance companies, to publicize the rebates, discounts, and price concessions they negotiate, via a website hosted by the U.S. secretary of health and human services.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger also co-sponsored the Elijah Cummings Lower Drug Costs Now Act, which grants Medicare Part D the power to negotiate prescription prices directly with drug companies.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger objected to President Trump's travel bans from certain predominantly Muslim countries and argued that they would aid jihadist propaganda by allowing a portrayal of the U.S. as an anti-Muslim country.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] She has voiced her support for stronger border security measures but opposes Trump's proposed wall.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger voted for a bill that included funding for border infrastructure, technology at ports of entry, and more customs and border protection officers and agents.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] She said she does not support "sanctuary cities" but also called the term "a campaign slogan a lot of people get caught up in".
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] She added that it "degrades the value of the conversation if we're not actually talking about what the real concern is." Spanberger called for a pathway to legal status for illegal immigrants who abide by the laws, work, and pay taxes.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Immigration and Customs Enforcement to be notified when undocumented immigrants attempt to purchase firearms.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] In 2022, she voted in favor of the Respect for Marriage Act.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] When Spanberger ran for governor in 2025, she was endorsed by the Human Rights Campaign, an LGBTQ advocacy group.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] In April 2006 she married Adam Spanberger, a University of Virginia-trained engineer, and her high school sweetheart.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] She helped run a Girl Scouts troop for her daughters when they were young.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] In 2014, the family moved to Henrico County.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] Before Spanberger became governor, they lived in Glen Allen, Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abigail-spanberger-p02] During her time in Congress, Spanberger roomed with colleague Mikie Sherrill, who was elected governor of New Jersey on the same day Spanberger was elected governor of Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Born to the former Elizabeth Woodson (1740–1791) and her husband Nathaniel Venable (1733–1804) at Slate Hill Plantation, a farm in what is now Worsham, Prince Edward County, then in the Colony of Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] His father operated plantations using enslaved labor, as well as represented Prince Edward County in the House of Burgesses and later in the Virginia House of Delegates, and helped found the first Presbyterian church in Prince Edward County.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] This younger Abraham Venable received a private education suitable to his class, then attended Hampden–Sydney College, which his father helped establish in 1775.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] He traveled to New Jersey for higher education at what was then the College of New Jersey (now Princeton University), and graduated in 1780.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] In addition to helping his father and overseers operate plantations in Prince Edward County, Venable studied law, but never married.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Various members of the Venable clan owned slaves in Prince Edward County in 1787.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] However, only his eldest brother Samuel W.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Venable (1756–1821) actually lived in Prince Edward County in 1787, having married the daughter of Judge Paul Carrington (and was taxed on 15 slaves (seven adults and eight children), four horses and 27 other livestock).
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Venable owned eight slaves (four adults and four children) in Prince Edward County, as well as three horses and nine cattle.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Their father Nathaniel Venable held a license to operate an ordinary (tavern/inn) in Prince Edward County and paid the taxes for William Anderson and Jessee Hamblet (probable overseers), as well as for 26 slaves (14 adults and 12 children), 8 horses and 44 other livestock.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] In the 1810 census for Prince Edward County, Abraham B.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Venable owned 31 slaves, most of the six men with that surname in the county.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Admitted to the bar in September 1784, Venable would come to develop a private legal practice centered at Farmville, the county seat of Prince Edward County, Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Other members of the local bar included Richard N.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Venable, Patrick Henry and Paul Carrington Jr. who were admitted in 1786 and 1788, respectively.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Charles Venable was the Prince Edward County sheriff when Virginia became a Commonwealth in 1776, succeeded by Nathaniel Venable, then other men.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Venable succeeded Robert Lawson as deputy Attorney General for the county in April 1788, and resigned the following May, succeeded by his cousin and fellow Princeton graduate, Joseph Venable.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Charles Venable became one of the county's 22 magistrates in 1785, but he and Thomas Haskins were removed in July 1787 pursuant to a warrant from Lieutenant Governor Beverly Randolph.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] At the Virginia Ratification Convention of 1788, Patrick Henry and Robert Lawson represented Prince Edward County.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Venable was becoming involved in politics, and won election to the Second Congress, serving from 1791 to 1799.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] There, he became chairman of the Committee on Elections in the Fourth Congress.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] After his congressional stint, Venable won election and thrice re-election as one of Prince Edward County's representative in the Virginia House of Delegates, mostly alongside Peter Johnston (who would ultimately become the body's Speaker), serving from 1801 until taking his interim U.S.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Fellow legislators in the Virginia General Assembly elected Venable to the Senate to fill a vacancy, serving from 1803 to 1804, when he resigned (after his father's death) to practice law in Richmond.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] A friend of Thomas Jefferson, Venable helped found and became president of Bank of Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Venable was one of the most prominent people to die in the Richmond Theatre fire in 1811.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] His ashes (and those of other victims, including Virginia Governor George William Smith) were placed under a rock at Monumental Church in Richmond.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] His brother Richard Nathaniel Venable, who had served as an officer during the Revolutionary War, would inherit Slate Hill Plantation, as well as continue the family political tradition as a lawyer, state senator and member of the Virginia Constitutional Convention of 1829.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Their nephew Abraham Watkins Venable would also serve in the U.S.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] Congress, representing a North Carolina district.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] The family's plantation house survives and is being investigated and restored.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/abraham-b-venable] In 2003 a historical marker was erected.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Harrison is the first governor of Virginia to have been born in the 20th century.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Harrison was born in Alberta, Virginia, the son of Albertis Sydney Harrison and Lizzie, (née Goodrich).
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] He has been widely reported as related to Benjamin Harrison V who signed the Declaration of Independence and two United States presidents, William Henry Harrison and Benjamin Harrison, the 9th and 23rd Presidents, however before his death, he found this to be false.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] He received a Bachelor of Laws degree from the University of Virginia Law School in 1928.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Harrison married Lacey Virginia Barkley in 1930.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] They had two children: Antoinette H Jamison and Albertis S.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Harrison III; and 6 grandchildren: Joseph D.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Goodrich Harrison, Monica Harrison Kopf, Virginia Lacey Jamison, and James Carper Jamison II.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Harrison went into legal practice in Lawrenceville, Virginia, where he became town attorney, before being elected commonwealth's attorney of Brunswick County.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] He was elected to the Senate of Virginia in 1947.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] He served there for ten years, before being elected Attorney General of Virginia in 1957.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Harrison resigned as attorney general in April 1961 to run for governor, winning election that November with 63.84% of the vote, defeating Republican H.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] His administration increased educational financing for new schools and laboratories and raised teachers' pay.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] He promoted the development of state-supported colleges and technical schools as well as improved vocational training.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] He helped to modernize state banking laws to attract investment and accelerated highway construction.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] He sat on the Virginia Supreme Court of Appeals, later renamed the Supreme Court of Virginia, from 1968 to 1981.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] In 1968 he chaired the Commission on Constitutional Revision that drafted the 1971 Constitution of Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] As Attorney General, Harrison was responsible for defending the state's resistance to school integration, as part of the Massive Resistance strategy endorsed and led by the state's political leader, United States Senator Harry F.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Part of Massive Resistance involved the closing of public schools in various Virginia cities and counties to prevent racially integrated classrooms.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] County School Board of Prince Edward County* (1952) was one of the companion cases to *Brown v.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Board of Education* (1954), but the Supreme Court had left enforcement to the local federal district judge.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Moreover, the Gray Commission of Byrd loyalists had recommended passage of various laws to avoid or delay integration.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] After opinions by the Virginia Supreme Court on January 19, 1959, as well as a three-judge federal panel overturned much of the new Virginia legislation, Governor J.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Lindsay Almond (previously attorney general) and Harrison decided not to defy those courts and allowed schools in Arlington and Norfolk to reopen.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] However the schools in Prince Edward County closed in 1958 and did not reopen until 1963, as white students used tuition grants to attend a private segregation academy at state expense, while black students were left to volunteer efforts.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Other problematic school closures, ultimately opened pursuant to federal court orders included those in Albemarle, Warren County and later New Kent County (the subject of the 1968 Supreme Court decision in *Green v.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] County School Board of New Kent County* (1968).
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Harrison told the board to comply unless they were willing to risk prosecution.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] By this time, he, like a number of other Byrd Democrats, had concluded that obstinate resistance to integration could not continue.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Another aspect of Massive Resistance involved new laws regulating attorney ethics, designed to attack practices of the NAACP, which was pursuing the desegregation actions.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Supreme Court deferred to an upcoming decision of the Virginia Supreme Court about those new ethics rules in *Harrison v.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] NAACP* (1959), but the case came before it twice more in *NAACP v.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Button* (1963) (which was reargued after Harrison resigned as attorney general to run for governor, and which Virginia lost under attorney general Robert Young Button.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] Harrison died of a heart attack at his home in Lawrenceville on January 23, 1995.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] He is buried in Oakwood Cemetery in Lawrenceville, Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/albertis-harrison] The courthouse in Lawrenceville is named in his honor.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Major-General **Alexander Spotswood** (12 December 1676 – 7 June 1740) was a British army officer, explorer and colonial administrator who served as the governor of Virginia from 1710 to 1722.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] After an unsatisfactory military career, in 1710 he was appointed as Virginia's governor, a post he held for twelve years.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] During that period, Spotswood engaged in the exploration of the territories beyond the western border, of which he was the first to see the economic potentials.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] As the governor of Virginia, Spotswood's first preoccupation was to make sea routes safe and fight against the pirates.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] After a long effort, the famous pirate Blackbeard was hunted down and killed in 1718.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In addition, Spotswood promoted the economic growth of the colony by founding the metallurgical settlements of Germanna; introduced the juridical instrument of habeas corpus; and introduced the rules for the commercial relations with Native Americans and those for the tobacco export trade.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] His tenure was characterised by a growing conflict with the Virginian political classes, which ended with his removal from office.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Years later, between 1730 and 1739, Spotswood was the Deputy Postmaster General of British America and, with his young friend Benjamin Franklin, extended the postal service network north of Williamsburg and improved its efficiency.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] At the outbreak of the War of Jenkins' Ear, Spotswood was called back into army service.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Promoted to major general, he was put in command of the colonial troops stationed in America with the task of preparing a military action against the Spanish stronghold of Cartagena de Indias, but, in Annapolis, where he was to consult with the local governors, he died suddenly in 1740.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Alexander Spotswood was born in Tangier, a city on the African shore of the Strait of Gibraltar, in 1676.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] 1638 – December 1709), the daughter of the Rev.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] 1655), who gave him an only son, Alexander.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Alexander's older half-brother (by his mother's first marriage to George Elliott) was Roger Elliott, who became one of the first governors of Gibraltar.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Both parents had Scottish origins, and the father, although economically ruined, could boast an illustrious lineage as a direct descendant of Robert the Bruce.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] His family had ancient baronial origins and had enjoyed great prestige until the time of the English Revolution.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] There had been illustrious Spotswoods, such as judge Sir Robert Spottiswoode (Alexander's grandfather) and Archbishop John Spottiswoode.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In 1684, following attacks of native Berber troops under the guide of governor Ali ben Abdallah, the city of Tangier was evacuated and the Spotswood family returned to England, where the father died in 1688.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In May 1693, at the age of sixteen, Spotswood enlisted in the English Army, the army of the Kingdom of England, with the rank of Ensign in the Earl of Bath's Regiment of Foot.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] He served first in Ireland and then in the Flanders.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Over the years, distinguishing himself for skill, courage and intelligence, he climbed the military hierarchy to the rank of lieutenant colonel.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The War of Spanish Succession broke out in 1701.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The main European powers fought each other throughout the following decade.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough, was in command of the English army stationed in central Europe.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Alexander Spotswood was part of it as deputy quartermaster general.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The troops remained quartered along the River Rhine for three years for the protection of the Netherlands.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Marlborough's army descended into Bavaria In 1704, taking the Franco-Bavarian forces by surprise.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The Battle of Blenheim took place on August 13 and ended in a major British victory.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] During the battle Spotswood was severely wounded in the chest during a heavy artillery attack.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Medicated on the battlefield, he was then sent to London to convalesce.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] He survived and kept the cannonball, which he used to show his friends and guests.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] He returned to the Flanders almost two years later.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] On 11 July 1708 he fought in the Battle of Oudenaarde, in the Netherlands, where his horse was killed and he fell prisoner to the French troops.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] But Duke of Marlborough, once again the winner of the battle, obtained his release by negotiating personally with the enemy, and Spotswood returned to his duties as quartermaster general to oversee the corn supply for the troops.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] However, his disappointment for the slowdown of his military career was growing.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Despite the good relationship with and the trust of his superiors, he was stuck in the rank of lieutenant colonel.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] His ambitions, fuelled by the many but never kept promises of promotion, were continuously frustrated.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In September 1709, having spent half of his life in the army, he took his leave and returned to London.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] During the war, Spotswood had made good friends not only with the Duke of Marlborough, but also with another of his commanders, George Hamilton, 1st Earl of Orkney.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Hamilton had held the post of governor of the colony of Virginia from 1704, but resided in London and was represented on American soil by a plenipotentiary delegate, with a nominal mandate as deputy governor.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In 1707 the deputy governor, Robert Hunter, had been captured by the French at sea and the colony was thus temporarily administered by a local government.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] At the suggestion of Hamilton himself, with perhaps an additional push by Marlborough, on February 18, 1710 Queen Anne appointed Spotswood as vice governor of Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] On April 3, Spotswood left for the Americas from the port of Spithead, in southern England, aboard the man-of-war HMS *Deptford*, in convoy with other British ships to ward off pirate attacks.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] At the beginning of the eighteenth century, Virginia was the most prosperous and populous of the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The inhabitants numbered around 80,000, including 20,000 slaves – most of them from the Bight of Biafra – employed in the vast tobacco plantations, at the service of a confederation of landowners.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The export of tobacco was still one of the most lucrative activities, but in recent times, due to the war against the French and the consequent closure of the Atlantic trade routes, it was not as rewarding as in the past, and overproduction had caused prices to drop.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In addition, in a period considered the golden age of piracy, the southern waters of British America were swarming with pirates and corsairs.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Coming from the Caribbean Sea, they sailed northwards along the American coastline as far as Virginia, making harmful raids.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Moreover, the land borders of the colony were at that time threatened by the original inhabitants of numerous Native American tribes.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] After ten weeks of good navigation, the convoy arrived in Virginia on June 20, and landed at the Hampton Roads bay (then known as *Kecoughtan*, the local Algonquian name).
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Three days later, Spotswood was in Williamsburg, the capital of the colony, where he was sworn in as governor, in the newly built Capitol.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] For the previous four years the colony had been ruled by the twelve members of the Governor's Council, who were appointed by the King.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Just like the fifty representatives of the House of Burgesses (who were elected by their Virginian peers), they belonged to the class of the great landowners whose real aim was to establish a *de facto* oligarchy.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Their interests often clashed with those of the Crown, and in the oversea territories their interests generally prevailed.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] On July 5 Spotswood made his first encounter with this problem.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] A resolution passed by the Governor's Council prior to his arrival had abolished the application of the annual payments for the tobacco lease and established the principle that tobacco be exchanged at a public sale.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Now, considering the low revenues, the Crown had decided to return to the old method of trade, but the Governor's Council, whose members controlled the public sale of tobacco, refused to implement the new rule.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood favoured the council's opinion, and this was the first public conflict of interests between the Crown, of which Spotswood would be for years to come a staunch supporter, and the wishes of the local ruling classes.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In addition, following the Crown's suggestions, he proposed to rebuild the College of William & Mary which had been destroyed by a fire five years earlier, and to establish a court of *oyer and terminer* (a sort of superior criminal court) that would have to meet every six months.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Meanwhile, another pressing issue reawakened his military vocation.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] A colonial militia of about 15,000 men was deployed to protect the land borders.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The majority of the troop came from the lower labouring classes, were poorly armed and operated under the orders of inexperienced commanders.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Since his arrival in Virginia, Spotswood had shown concern about the colony's vulnerability and had started to reorganise and strengthen the militia to match the task of defending the colony.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] During the summer of 1711, he personally supervised the installation of a series of cannons in the ports between Yorktown and Jamestown to prevent a possible French naval invasion.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] That was the beginning of the so-called Tuscarora War.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood, well aware that it was a real war, considering how badly equipped the militia was, requested weapons and ammunition from England, which however would take a few months to arrive.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] His aim being to prevent other tribes from joining the Tuscarora revolt, he headed south with the 15,000 militia men and stopped on the bank of the Nottoway River.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The local tribes proved to be well disposed towards the British and offered them military support against the Tuscarora.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] As a guarantee, Spotswood demanded that each tribe deliver two of the young sons of the tribal chiefs as hostages, to be educated in Williamsburg at the College of William & Mary.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The objective was twofold: to give them a Christian education, so that they could return later as missionaries to their own tribes – within the framework of a wider operation to civilise the Indians –, and at the same time to guarantee for a certain period of time the friendship of those tribes.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In early December, hostages from several tribes arrived in Williamsburg.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The House of Burgesses, however, was not happy about this resolution, as they would have liked a more direct military action against the Indians.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Between the summer and the fall of the following year, some of the rebel Tuscarora chiefs were captured and transferred to North Carolina for trial.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The War of Spanish Succession ended in April 1713, and the British victory led to the reopening of the Atlantic trade routes and the annexation of new colonies.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The Virginian economy was revitalised, and in particular the tobacco export trade which in recent years had been severely affected by the conflict.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Tobacco in those days was also used as a means of payment and was sold by the weight.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] To make more profit traders often added poor quality to high-quality varieties, causing prices to drop.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Previous colonial governments had made attempts on several occasions to regulate the trade, but nothing had ever really come of it.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] So, in November 1713, Spotswood, to bring the tobacco market under control and set limits to the practices of the big landowners, submitted to the House of Burgesses the *Tobacco Inspection Act*.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The new law, supported by the Governor's Council, required tobacco to be inspected before shipment to Europe.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In Spotswood's intentions there would thus be a reduction in the quantities exported, resulting in an increase in the quality of the goods and a consequent increase in demand and in price.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] To soften the opposition of the House of Burgesses', Spotswood appointed as inspectors some of the representatives in favour of his proposal, which was finally approved.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The reform, however, produced only partial results compared with the expectations: prices did not rise immediately, and the inspection procedure was disliked by the landowners.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Yet another initiative by Spotswood caused him to lose the favour of the Virginian elite.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In December 1714, he had the *Indian Trade Act* passed.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] All commercial activities with the Indians south of the James River were placed under the exclusive control of the Virginia Indian Company, established with an allocation of £10,000.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The measure should have put an end to the illegal trade that took place along the border and which, according to Spotswood, was one of the reasons for the unrest of the Indians, and at the same time was against the interests of the colonials who were trading privately with the Indian tribes.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] William Byrd II, an influential member of the Governor's Council who wanted Spotswood's position for himself, was in control of much of the trade with the Indians, particularly the Cherokee, to whom he sold cloth and weapons.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Shortly after the law was passed, Byrd left for England on personal business, but certainly also with the intention of bringing Spotswood discredit in the various branches of the royal administration.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The disputes between Spotswood and the members of the House of Burgesses grew until they degenerated in 1715.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] During an assembly held between August and September the representatives, instead of concentrating on the problems of the colony's defence as was Spotswood's recommendation, challenged the *Indian Trade Act* and the *Tobacco Inspection Act*.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The discontent generated by the latter among landowners and merchants had played a fundamental role in the last elections of the House of Burgesses.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Almost all the representatives who had previously supported the act had lost their seat, and a large section of the newly elected were in disagreement.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The scarce rainfall of the previous year had provided the tobacco traders with reasons to justify the request of being allowed to sell all the tobacco produced, regardless of its quality, ignoring therefore the provisions of the *Tobacco Inspection Act*.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] After five weeks of time-wasting discussions – which irritated him all the more now that some Indian tribes at the border were becoming hostile, putting the application of the *Indian Trade Act* at risk –, Spotswood put an end to the debates and closed the assembly.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In early 1716, an anonymous letter from Virginia to the London Board of Trade denounced Spotswood for alleged violations of the law, even more strongly than previous still anonymous letters, and accused him of greed and tyranny.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Despite the contrasts with the House of Burgesses, during the middle years of his tenure, Spotswood concentrated mainly on the exploration beyond the western frontier, beyond the foothills of Piedmont.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] On account of the Tuscarora war, the situation at the border had become tense again, but after one hundred years of periods of war followed by periods of peace, the British and the Indians had learned that, in the absence of a winner, they had better try and live together.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] To deal with the Indian threat, since his arrival in Virginia Spotswood had sent rangers to patrol the border and explorers in search of a pass through the Blue Ridge Mountains.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In the spring of 1714, he personally joined an expedition to explore the upper reaches of the York and Mattaponi Rivers.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] These explorations took place for precise strategic purposes.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In the summer of 1714, having sufficiently secured the borders, Spotswood went into action by establishing two forest settlements beyond the Tidewater border, which for the past century had signed the limit of British expansion.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The first settlement, Fort Christanna, stood on the southern bank of the Meherrin River, near the border with North Carolina.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Built for the headquarters of the Virginia Indian Company, the company created under the *Indian Trade Act*, the fort housed a school for the education of Indians to the Christian way of life.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood's objectives, in addition to those of immediate strategic utility already pursued at the time of the Tuscarora war, were ambitious: to turn the traditionally semi-nomadic Indians into a resident population.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The second settlement established by Spotswood was Germanna, situated north of a bend of the Rapidan River.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] A group of refugees from the Palatinate, arrived in America in 1709 with the approval of Queen Anne following the destruction of their lands during the War of Spanish Succession, had settled in the region and they had discovered deposits of silver and iron.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Initially, nine families of German Protestants settled in Germanna, working for the local smelting furnaces.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In October 1714, news came that Queen Anne had died in early August.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] 1716 saw the results of the previous explorations in the western territories.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] On June 12, Spotswood reported to the Governor's Council that some rangers had found a passage through the mountains and offered himself to lead an expedition beyond Piedmont, in regions then unknown.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The Council approved the proposal, on the consideration of its commercial and strategic potential.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood left Williamsburg with a few men on August 20, 1716, and headed for Germanna, where a meeting point had been fixed.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Here the expeditionary force was formed, and on 29 August a group of sixty-three men set off for the mountains.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The group included influential members of the settlers' community, servants, rangers, native guides and a good number of horses and dogs.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The group went up the Rapidan River, hunting animals and toasting the new king, through a dense bushy area crossed by numerous water streams.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] During the march, some men contracted measles and were left behind in a field hospital readily set up and manned by rangers.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The rest of the group proceeded under the threats of bears and rattlesnakes, until they reached the source of the Rapidan River on the Blue Ridge Mountains, on 5 September.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] They crossed the mountains passing through a gorge by the name of Swift Run Gap at an altitude of 720 m, bordered by two mountain peaks.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood named George the higher of the two in honour of the king, and his companions named the other Alexander in his honour.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] They descended from the ridge towards the Shenandoah Valley: the first Westerners to set eyes and foot on it.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Crossing woods and meadows populated by elks and buffalos, after about ten kilometres they reached the bottom of the valley and the course of the Shenandoah River, which was renamed Euphrates.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Gun shots were fired here in honour of the king and a great toast was held.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood engraved the king's name on a rock and in an empty wine bottle introduced a card containing the British claim on the river and its territory.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] On September 7, the company left for Germanna, and in ten days was back in Williamsburg.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The following winter, Spotswood gave each member of the expedition a miniature gold horseshoe with engraved in Latin: *Sic juvat transcendere montes* ("This is the way to cross the mountains").
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Since then, the expedition was also known as "Knights of the Golden Horseshoe Expedition" and described by Spotswood's biographer, Walter Havighurst, as "the most romantic episode in the history of Virginia".
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] It played a leading historical role not so much for the practical results it achieved, but for the impulse and the inspiration it provided for those who later wanted to venture in the exploration of the interior of the American colonies.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The expedition also left considerable traces in American literature.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] A few months after the company's return, a humanities professor at the College of William & Mary, Arthur Blackamore wrote a short poem in Latin celebrating the expedition: *Expeditio Ultramontana*.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The original Latin text, considered to be among the best examples of Latin poetry in 18th century America, has been lost, but the English version that George Seagood produced in 1729 survives in its entirety.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Over a century later, in 1835, William Alexander Caruthers published a chivalric novel, *The Knights of the Golden Horse-Shoe*, telling a somewhat revisited history of the expedition.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In the 20th century, the poet Gertrude Claytor wrote a commemorative poem of the Golden Horseshoe Expedition.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Engraved on a bronze plaque, in 1934 it was posted near Swift Run Gap.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The success of the Transmontane Expedition was welcomed in the London administrative offices, but in less than a year a severe blow to the Spotswood's peace of mind came from the capital.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] At the beginning of the year 1717, a large group of influential London merchants wrote a letter to the Board of Trade declaring that the legislation promoted by Spotswood harmed the commercial interests of both the motherland and Virginia itself.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The merchants reported that, due to the corruption of the inspectors by the landowners, the lower quality production was not only still on the market – in contradiction with the purposes of the *Tobacco Inspection Act* – but had actually overtaken the higher quality varieties.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The Virginia Indian Company's monopoly on trade with Indians also deprived the merchants of a lucrative market, and this, coupled with heavy export regulations, made their activities unprofitable.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The merchants therefore asked for the abolition of those laws which they considered an obstacle to the development of trade.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The king thus put a veto on the *Tobacco Inspection Act* and on the *Indian Trade Act*, and Spotswood was forced to revoke both.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] William Byrd, in a letter from England to Philip Ludwell, a member of the Governor's Council, wrote that he had contributed to the abrogation of those laws and to the weakening of the position and influence of the governor.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The House of Burgesses opposed public funding of Fort Christanna, which had to be dismantled as a consequence, although Spotswood feared that this would destabilise the border, leaving local Indian tribes without British support and at the mercy of the Carolina tribes.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] This put an end to the *Indian Trade Act*, but not to the principles it sought to implement, which remained central in Spotswood's policy for years to come.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] As for the *Tobacco Inspection Act*, on the other hand, years later, in 1730, the same measures were successfully re-proposed and did not meet as strong an opposition as previously.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In all probability, the hostility of the House of Burgesses, rather than to a genuine intention to favour trade, was due to its tendency to oppose the actions of the governor, who had been fighting for years with the representatives for the effective control of the colony.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] During this period of time, in addition to William Byrd's mission to London, other members of the Governor's Council were openly taking position against Spotswood.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The most determined among them was the Reverend James Blair, delegate of the Bishop of London and president of the College of William & Mary, one of the most powerful men in the colony, who had already been behind the dismissal of past governors Edmund Andros and Francis Nicholson.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The reason for this opposition was once again to be found in the resistance, on the part of the Virginians, to royal prerogatives affirmed by Spotswood, who claimed for the governor the right to appoint judges in criminal trials (through procedures called *oyer and terminer*).
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The members of the council, on the other hand, claimed to be the only ones entitled to do so.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In any case, the Virginian popular opinion supported the governor, who was particularly popular with the small landowners, the yeomen class.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] And, despite Byrd's scheming against him in London and the revocation of his laws, Spotswood still enjoyed the protection of the King's ministers and of the members of the Board of Trade.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In a letter sent in August 1717 to Secretary of State Joseph Addison, Spotswood reported that the only sources of concern left to impair the peace and quiet of the colony were piracy and the aggressive nature of the Indians.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Just a few months earlier, several armed Seneca gangs had moved from the Province of New York to the Virginia border, where they had engaged in raids and robberies.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In March 1717, some chiefs of the Catawba tribe had gone to Fort Christanna to discuss a trade treaty with the British and Spotswood, who had long-awaited the good disposition of the Indians, had joined them.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In the days of the meeting an episode took place which risked compromising the negotiations.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] One night, some Seneca or Mohawk Indians – enemies of the Catawba – entered the fort, where the governor was lying asleep, and killed some members of the delegation, who were not bearing arms as Spotswood had imposed.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Initially, the Catawba accused the British of having betrayed them and started to leave, but Spotswood, who was in danger of seeing his plans to secure the border undermined, sent a contingent to recover the abducted, reaffirmed his friendship with the Indians, and promised them greater protection.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In the end, the Catawba agreed to trade at Fort Christanna and leave some of their children there to study, and the border situation seemed to improve, at least temporarily.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The other looming threat were the pirates, who attacked ports and robbed ships, greatly hampering trade.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The most famous and feared among them, Edward Teach, who went down in history as Blackbeard, had recently returned to sail the seas, having received the King's pardon and having later surrendered to the governor of North Carolina, Charles Eden, who was probably in cahoots with him.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] When Blackbeard attacked a convoy of ships in front of Charleston Harbor in May 1718, looting and taking prisoners, the Carolina residents sought help from neighbouring Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Although he did not have a specific mandate from the king – which was necessary for the arrest and trial of pirates –, Spotswood decided to intervene, wary of Carolina's possibilities of dealing with the problem.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] He quickly had former *Queen Anne's Revenge* quartermaster William Howard arrested, who had apparently retired from piracy and lived in Virginia, suspecting that he was still in contact with Blackbeard.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] From Howard, later pardoned, he learned that Blackbeard was with a few men in one of his usual shelters, the Ocracoke Inlet.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Ocracoke was in North Carolina, out of his jurisdiction, but Spotswood was now determined to capture the pirate as quickly as possible, dead or alive, even by violating the sovereignty of another colony.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] So, without waiting for the authorization of the House of Burgesses, he sent two warships against Blackbeard under the command of Navy Lieutenant Robert Maynard.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] On November 22, 1718, after five days of search, the pirates were taken by surprise.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Maynard, aboard HMS *Pearl*, attacked Blackbeard's ship, who was killed in a short and bloody fight.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Nine of his men died with him, and Maynard lost a dozen of his men.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Two days later, Maynard returned to Jamestown with fifteen prisoners, who were later hanged, and Blackbeard's severed head was stuck on the tip of the bowsprit.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The apparent quiet at the borders was the background of new conflicts within the colony.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Some members of the House of Burgesses published a controversial pamphlet in which they reported of illegal proceedings on the part of Spotswood and in particular of the lack of prior consultation with Governor Eden.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] It appears that Spotswood was highly likely aware of Eden's political weaknesses and of his compromises with the pirates, and that he purposely omitted to seek his cooperation.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] At the same time, relations with the Governor's Council also reached a critical point.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In the early months of 1719, with the dispute over the pirates unresolved, a hard dispute arose over the powers of some sectors of the Church.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Led by James Blair and other members of the council, a first group was in favour of the current law which provided for the clergy to be directly appointed by an assembly of parishioners and without the approval of the governor.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Both sides turned to the Bishop of London, accusing each other of interference and abuse of power.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The Bishop of London then called for an assembly of all the clergymen of Virginia to take place in Williamsburg in April at the College of William & Mary, in the presence of Blair and Spotswood.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] This growing hostility of the council had already manifested itself during the previous year and Spotswood, unable to bring it under control, had tried to change its composition.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In November 1718, he asked the Board of Trade to remove some advisers hostile to him, including Blair and Byrd, who was still in London, and to replace them with men he trusted.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The Board of Trade did not fully comply with Spotswood's requests: only two of the men he proposed were appointed and the only councillor removed, Byrd – who returned to Virginia early in 1720 – was almost immediately reinstated.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Unable to get rid of them, the governor tried to make peace with the members of the council.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Byrd, who was now resident in Virginia and could therefore be more easily controlled, became Spotswood's point of reference.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The two met at the Capitol and resolved to cooperate.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] On April 29, 1720, during the next assembly of the council, the governor and the councillors officially declared their resolve to work in harmony from then on.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In this more relaxed situation, Spotswood obtained land concessions near Germanna and the western frontier, for a total of approximately 86,000 acres, where he began to build his private residence.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The Spotswood estate formed the core of the Spotsylvania County, which was established in 1720 in his honour.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Meanwhile, the buildings of the Governor's Palace and of the Bruton Parish Church in Williamsburg, which Spotswood had personally collaborated to design, were completed.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The Governor's palace, in particular, was the subject of criticism for its pomp and excessive costs, but its architecture was appreciated, so much so that in its time it became a model for all residences of prestige.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The truce made official in 1720, although sincerely wanted by the parties involved, appears as a prelude to the final attack against Spotswood.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] During the summer of the following year, Byrd and Blair left for England, there to reiterate more forcefully their efforts against the governor.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Despite the territorial expansion established with the Expedition over the mountains, Spotswood deemed it necessary for Great Britain to expand further northwest, as far as the Great Lakes, to gain strategic advantage in view of an imminent war against the French.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] He had already obtained an accurate map of the entire western area of the Mississippi River System, hitherto virtually unknown to the British, to be used for an expedition to Lake Erie, where Spotswood intended to establish a settlement.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In February 1720, Spotswood proposed to go on a secret mission to London to present these ideas to the government and to illustrate in detail how it was possible and necessary to conquer Spanish Florida by attacking the Spaniards in St.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Augustine, in order to prevent the French fleet from entering the waters of the Thirteen colonies from the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The secret missions never took place, and Spotswood, during his last two years as governor, concentrated instead on resolving the Indian question.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] If piracy was in rapid decline after Blackbeard's death, the problems caused by the hostile and bellicose Indian tribes were increasingly worrying.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The first outbreak was on the Maryland border, and was fuelled by hostilities between the neighbouring tribes and those of Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In the fall of 1720, tribes from Maryland attacked plantations in the Northern Neck, whereupon Spotswood, with the support of the governor of Maryland, called a meeting with the ambassadors of the five Iroquois Confederation tribes who were in conflict with the Virginia Indians.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] During the meeting, which took place in Williamsburg in October 1721, three of the five ambassadors died, possibly poisoned.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Despite this event, of which the Iroquois suspected the Virginia Indians, an agreement was reached by which the Potomac River became the frontier between the Indians of Virginia and the Iroquois, and no Indian was to cross it without the authorization of the British.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Encouraged by the results, Spotswood began organizing a general meeting with the Iroquois tribes and their *Sachems* (supreme leaders), with the collaboration with the governors of Maryland, Pennsylvania, and New York.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] By June 1722, the time was ripe for Spotswood to sail from Virginia with one delegate from the Governor's Council and one from the House of Burgesses, and many gifts for the Iroquois from the Virginia Indians and from the colony's government.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] He set sail for New York and from there, along with Pennsylvania governor William Keith and some New York government spokesmen, he left by land for the city of Albany, located on the banks of the Hudson River.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The delegation, which arrived in Albany on August 20, was the most representative the British had ever set up in the Thirteen Colonies, and their commitment must have impressed the Indians.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Within a few days they were joined by the leaders and warriors of the Mohicans, Oneida, Cayuga, Onondaga, and Seneca; practically all the nations in the Iroquois Confederation, followed later by the Powhatans and other tribes from Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] He gave the Indian Chiefs pearl necklaces as a gift to demonstrate British good will.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Then he asked officially for confirmation of their commitment of the previous year to put an end to the raids in Piedmont and to respect the natural boundaries of the Blue Ridge Mountains and of the Potomac River.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The Indians took about ten days to answer, then the agreement, which was Spotswood's main objective, was ratified.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood also made a personal gift to the Indians of fine fabrics and work tools.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Then he left by ship along the Hudson River, heading for the open sea.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] When he arrived in Williamsburg, Spotswood learned that, despite the popular support he enjoyed, the king had decided to revoke his position as governor.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] On September 25, with Spotswood back in Williamsburg, James Blair, who had been absent for the past 12 months, and the new governor, Hugh Drysdale, an Irishman, arrived in the New World on the same ship.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The Drysdale nomination, dated April 3, 1722, was made official and Drysdale was sworn in as governor on September 27.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Historians are in disaccord when explaining the reasons behind the removal of Spotswood from office.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Walter Havighurst identified Spotswood's character as main cause; a strong, sharp, and sometimes authoritarian character, prone to the regime of obedience in the military tradition, which the Virginia aristocracy was neither used to nor willing to accept.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In fact, during the twelve years at the helm in Virginia, the governor ended up into a conflict with each one of the strong powers of the colony, as well as with the more influential of his own men, from merchants to large landowners.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The causes of his removal, which are never explicitly expressed in the official documents of the time, must be sought, according to Havighurst, in the controversy over the *oyer and terminer* courts, or over the more recent controversy on the clergymen's appointment.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The evaluations of Spotswood's contemporaries were also discordant.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Harsh criticisms of some aspects of his work can be found in the writings of James Blair and William Byrd, whose letters have been preserved.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Equally high praise, however, can be found in Robert Beverley (see his *History and Present State of Virginia*), who was one of the first historians born in Virginia, as well as Spotswood's companion in the Transmontane Expedition.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Another Spotswood's political ally, Hugh Jones, professor at the College of William & Mary, wrote in 1724, (*The Present State of Virginia*), that Virginia had become more civilised in the twelve years of Spotswood's tenure than in the previous one hundred years.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Among modern historians prevails a generally positive opinion about the Spotswood administration: brilliant and significant in its character; a strong guide in a period of economic growth and cultural development.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Historian John Fiske, in the late nineteenth century, described Spotswood as one of the best and most capable governors of the British colonial period in America and praised him in particular for the founding of the Germanna smelting plant and for the audacity of the Transmontane Expedition.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The same opinion was expressed by historian Virginius Dabney, who described Spotswood as the most celebrated among the governors of Virginia during the colonial period.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] After the experience of government, Spotswood moved to his private residence situated along the Rappahannock River, near Germanna, where he devoted himself to the administration of his large estate and to the management of his metallurgical enterprise.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Part of the production of iron and cast iron was exported to England and the rest was destined to the local market.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] For the other activities, mining and agriculture, Spotswood made use at first of the Palatine refugees he had introduced in Germanna almost ten years earlier, and when the contract that bound them to him expired, he resorted to slaves from Africa.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood's activities also included raising livestock, producing naval supplies, pitch, tar, and turpentine.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] However, having assigned land to himself in large quantities during his tenure as governor, he was accused in some circles of land grabbing.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] So, with the intention of coming to an advantageous agreement with the British Government in London on the amount of taxes due, and at the same time consolidating his right of ownership, Spotswood left for England in 1724.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] His stay in England lasted longer than expected on account of some complications, which included quantifying the extension of the land in his possession and the amount of tax to be paid.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Up till now, at age forty-eight, Spotswood had remained a bachelor waiting for the opportunity to marry a woman of high social standing.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Now, on this occasion and in the capital, shortly after his arrival, Spotswood married Anne Butler Brayne, born in 1700, the daughter of a London esquire and godchild of James Butler, 2nd Duke of Ormond.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] They had four children, two boys and two girls.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Having obtained favourable tax conditions, in February 1729 Spotswood crossed the Atlantic for the fourth and final time, with his wife and children.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] During his absence, the volume of production in the metallurgical plant had dropped and some slaves had escaped, but this had not affected the activities in the estate as a whole.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] On the contrary, the prolonged active state of the furnaces made this the first stable site of this type in all of North America.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] As a private citizen, Spotswood financed the construction of a church in Germanna and began building another private residence in his own forest along the Rappahannock River.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The structure, which was destroyed in the 1750s, had a park and a cherry tree boulevard, and was larger than the Williamsburg Governor's Palace.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] During this period, Spotswood made peace with William Byrd.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] After the completion of the building Byrd wrote a detailed description of the residence, which he called an "enchanted castle", and of the solitary and measured lifestyle of its owner.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] During this time, Spotswood acquired another property near Yorktown, called Temple Farm.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] A few decades later the house, known as Moore House from the surname of Spotswood's son-in-law who inherited it, was the theatre of a crucial episode of the American Revolution, when in 1781 General Charles Cornwallis signed the final British surrender.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] During the last few years of his life, Spotswood stayed away from the frenzy of political life.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] At the time of Byrd's visit, some ministers in London were thinking of offering him (as Byrd testifies) the post of governor of the colony of Jamaica, with the task of taking Spanish Havana with a military action.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] However, nothing came of it, as it was eventually decided to resort to more peaceful ways of dealing with the Spaniards.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood accepted instead a less up-front mandate, which allowed him to return to projects developed during his years as governor: in 1730 he was appointed with a ten-year term Deputy Postmaster General of British America.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] At the time, the postal system covered only the coastal strip extending from New England to Pennsylvania up to Philadelphia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Virginia, cut off from courier routes, received mail once every two weeks.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In 1732, Spotswood extended the postal system to Williamsburg, where the mail started to arrive on a weekly basis.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood also entered into a partnership with the young publisher Benjamin Franklin, with whom he developed a personal friendship, appointing him, in 1737, postmaster for his city, Philadelphia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In October 1739, due to the constant attacks on the English merchant navy by Spanish naval ships, Britain declared war on Spain.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The conflict would go down in history as the war of Jenkins' Ear, named after an English captain whose ear was cut off by the Spaniards.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood, who had not lost interest in military affairs, proposed to the general command of London that he personally recruit a regiment of volunteers to be employed in South America.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Having obtained approval, he was appointed major general and quartermaster of the troops stationed in America, crowning thus with a promotion his military career.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] He was to be the leader and the organiser of a military expedition against the Spanish stronghold of Cartagena de Indias, in present-day Colombia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] At the beginning of the following May, Spotswood travelled to Annapolis, Maryland, to consult with the local governors, wait there for the arrival of his troops and later to set sail with them.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] But in Annapolis he was taken ill, and his death came quickly, on June 7, 1740, at the age of sixty-four.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] The expedition to Cartagena was postponed for a year, when the British forces placed the city under siege, but were utterly defeated.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood's body was probably buried in Annapolis, but it is possible that it was brought back home to his Temple Farm property near Yorktown and buried near the York River.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] In any case, the memory of Spotswood, and in particular of his government, lasted in Williamsburg for a long time to come.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alexander-spotswood] It was revealed in episode 4 of the 10th season of *Who Do You Think You Are?* that through his daughter, Dorothea, Alexander Spotswood was pop star Hilary Duff's seventh great-grandfather.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] In its earliest usage, *alma mater* was an honorific title for various mother goddesses, especially Ceres or Cybele.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] Later, in Catholicism, it became a title for Mary, mother of Jesus.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] By the early 17th century, the nursing mother became an allegory for universities.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] Used by many schools in Europe and North America, it has special association with the University of Bologna, whose motto *Alma Mater Studiorum* ("nurturing mother of studies") emphasizes its role in originating the modern university.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] Several university campuses in North America display artistic representations of *Alma Mater*, depicted as a robed woman wearing a laurel wreath crown.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] The earliest and of these is the bronze *Alma Mater* statue at Columbia University, designed in 1901 by Daniel Chester French.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] In the US the term *alma mater* is often used to describe a school song.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] Although *alma* (nourishing) was a common epithet for Ceres, Cybele, Venus, and other mother goddesses, it was not frequently used in conjunction with *mater* in classical Latin.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] After the fall of Rome, the term was used in Christian liturgy to describe Jesus' mother, Mary.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] "Alma Redemptoris Mater" is a well-known eleventh century antiphon devoted to Mary.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] The earliest documented use of the term to refer to a university is in 1600, when the University of Cambridge printer, John Legate, began using an emblem for the university press.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] The first-known appearance of the device is in William Perkins', *A Golden Chain*, a book first printed by Legate in 1600.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] On the title-page, the Latin phrase *Alma Mater Cantabrigia* ("nourishing mother Cambridge") is inscribed on a pedestal bearing a lactating woman wearing a mural crown.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] In reference works of English etymology, often the first university-related usage is cited as 1710, when an academic mother figure is mentioned in a remembrance of Henry More by Richard Ward.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] Many historic European universities have adopted *Alma Mater* as part of the Latin translation of their official name.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] The Latin name of the University of Bologna, *Alma Mater Studiorum* (nourishing mother of studies), refers to its status as the oldest continuously operating university in the world.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] At other European universities, such as the Alma Mater Lipsiensis in Leipzig, Germany, or Alma Mater Jagiellonica, Poland, the title emphasizes historic ties to a founding city or dynasty.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] The Alma Mater Europaea in Salzburg, Austria, an international university founded by the European Academy of Sciences and Arts in 2010, uses the term as its official name.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] In the United States, the College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, Virginia, has been called the "Alma Mater of the Nation" because of its ties to the founding of the country.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] At Queen's University in Kingston, Ontario, and the University of British Columbia in Vancouver, British Columbia, the main student government is known as the Alma Mater Society.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] Sculptures of *Alma Mater* are found on several North American university campuses.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] In 1901, to commemorate the opening of the Low Library, Columbia University commissioned Daniel Chester French to design a bronze statue for the library's steps.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] French chose the *Alma Mater* to allegorically embody the university without depicting its founder, King George II.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] A similar sculpture, cast in 1919 by Mario Korbel, sits on the main entrance steps at the University of Havana.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] Other tributes to *Alma Mater* include Lorado Taft's *1929 sculpture* at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign and Cyrus Dallin's 1925 sculpture at the Mary Institute in 1925, commissioned by Washington University supporters.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/alma-mater] An altarpiece mural in Yale University's Sterling Memorial Library, painted in 1932 by Eugene Savage, depicts the *Alma Mater* as a bearer of light and truth, standing in the midst of figures representing the arts and sciences.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Page was born and lived at Rosewell Plantation in Gloucester County.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] He was the son of Alice (Grymes) and Mann Page.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] His great-great-grandfather was Colonel John Page (1628–1692), an English merchant from Middlesex who emigrated to Virginia with his wife Alice Lucken Page and settled in Middle Plantation.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] John Page graduated from the College of William and Mary in 1763, where he was a close friend and college classmate of Thomas Jefferson, with whom he exchanged, as fellow revolutionaries, much correspondence.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] After he graduated from William and Mary, he then served under George Washington in an expedition during the French and Indian War.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] He also served during the American Revolutionary War as an officer in the Virginia state militia, raising a regiment from Gloucester County and supplementing it with personal funds.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] During that war, he attained the rank of colonel.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Page was a Fifth Virginia Convention delegate in 1776.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Page was also instrumental in getting his wife Frances' brother, Nathaniel Burwell, appointed to the Governor's council, and together, Page and Burwell opposed Lord Dunmore's proclamation against Patrick Henry.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Page and Burwell built the council whose membership read like a list of Patriots, shaping the American Revolution against Britain.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] The revolutionary Virginia legislature elected Page as the Lieutenant Governor of Virginia and served 1776–1779.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] However, when voters were asked to select delegates to the Virginia Ratifying Convention of 1788, they chose Warner Lewis alongside Thomas Smith, rather than this man.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Nonetheless, the Page family remained politically powerful in Gloucester County, as voters elected Mann Page to succeed him for a term.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] However, they selected Mordecai Cooke and James Baytop, who became their repeatedly reelected delegates in Richmond.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] He was a Congressman from March 4, 1789, to March 3, 1797.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] He was elected a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1792.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] After his terms in Congress, Page again won election as one of Gloucester County's representatives to the Virginia House of Delegates in 1797, alongside William Hall.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] However, only Hall won re-election in 1798, as Mordecai Cooke and several other men won the second seat.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] He was an unsuccessful candidate in the 1797 Virginia gubernatorial election, and ran in the 1799 U.S.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Senate special election, in which he was defeated by Wilson Cary Nicholas.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] In 1800, Gloucester County voters again selected Page to sit alongside Hall and reelected neither, presumably in part because fellow legislators elected Page as Governor of Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] He also tried to return to Congress in 1801, but was defeated by Federalist nominee and former state delegate John Stratton.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Page became the Governor of Virginia in 1802 and served three consecutive one-year terms until 1805, the maximum allowed by the state constitution.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] After the end of his tenure, Page accepted a federal appointment as United States commissioner of loans for Virginia and held office until his death.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] In 1765, Page married Frances Burwell, daughter of Col.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Together, Frances and John were the parents of twelve children, though only seven lived to adulthood: Mann (1766–1813), Robert (b.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Of the seven who survived to adulthood, five married children of Gov.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Thomas Nelson, thereby forging a significant alliance between the Page and Nelson families; there was also Burwell blood on both sides, the Burwells by these marriages becoming close relatives of the Page and Nelson families for at least three generations.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] After the death of his first wife in 1784, Page remarried, this time to early American poet Margaret Lowther Page, who hosted a literary salon at the Rosewell Plantation.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Page, himself also a poet, wrote several poems about national political issues, including Shays' Rebellion and the Virginia Religious Disestablishment Act (Virginia Statute for Religious Freedom).
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] He and Margaret were parents to eight children.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] However, only three lived to see adulthood: Margaret (b.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Page's niece by marriage, Judith Lomax, was also a poet.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Page died in Richmond, Virginia, on October 11, 1808.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] The Page family is one of the First Families of Virginia.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Its members include Colonel John Page, Governor John Page, his brother Mann Page, Thomas Nelson Page a leading proponent of the Lost Cause myth, and Virginian Railway builder William Nelson Page.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Page County, Virginia, located in the Shenandoah Valley, was formed in 1831 and named for Governor John Page.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Also bearing his name is a residence hall at the College of William and Mary.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Writing to his friend Jefferson shortly after the Declaration of Independence was published, Page said of the Declaration and the Revolution: "We know the race is not to the swift nor the battle to the strong.
[src:john-page-virginia-politician/john-page-virginia-politician] Do you not think an angel rides in the whirlwind and directs this storm".
